Description Cluster Group

How does DescriptionClustergroup relates with Price and Reviews

we wanted to see if the cluster group really meant any difference with respect to price and reviews Looks like the clusters are actually different, 1.listings with higher number of reviews and lower price are clustered together

2.Listings with medium reviews and medium price

3.Listings with low reviews but higher price

tempdf<- dflistings %>%group_by(Description_ClusterGroup)%>%summarize(PriceAverage = mean(price),Reviews= mean(number_of_reviews))

ggplot(tempdf, aes(log(PriceAverage), log(as.integer(Reviews))  ,color = Description_ClusterGroup )) +  
  geom_point(size = 10) +
  ggtitle("Description Cluster group with respect to Price and Number of Reviews") +
  xlab("Average Price") +
  ylab("Number of Reviews")

Number of Listing by Property Type

It can be clearly noticed that more than 60% of the listings are type ‘Apartment’ and thus dominates the listing on Airbnb followed by Condominium and Houses,with almost negible amount of other types! The possible reason would be that most of Hosts on Airbnb use listings as investments where the initial cost for property_type would be lower than other property type.

We replace all the other categories from Property type to others since,their presence would not provide any good insights about the data

ggplot(dflistings, aes(x = property_type, y = (..count..)/sum(..count..) ,fill = property_type )) + 
geom_bar(width = 0.25) + 
    theme(axis.text.x=element_text(angle=90,hjust=1)) +
    ggtitle("Listing Percent By property Type") + 
    ylab("Percentage")+
      xlab("PropertyType")

# Change the Property type for Listing to Others except for Apartments,Condominiums and Houses

dflistings$property_type <- as.character(dflistings$property_type)

dflistings$property_type<-ifelse (dflistings$property_type == 'Apartment' | dflistings$property_type == 'Condominium'  |  dflistings$property_type == 'House' , dflistings$property_type, "Others")

dflistings$property_type <- as.factor(dflistings$property_type)

Number of Listing by Room Type

A similar trend can be also seem with respect to the room type ,where Entire Home dominated the count and makes up for 60% of the total listings followed by private room and a very less amount of Shared rooms!

room_types_counts <- table(dflistings$room_type)
room_types <- names(room_types_counts)
counts <- as.vector(room_types_counts)
percentages <- scales::percent(round(counts/sum(counts), 2))
room_types_percentages <- sprintf("%s (%s)", room_types, percentages)
room_types_counts_df <- data.frame(group = room_types, value = counts)

# Plot
pie <- ggplot(room_types_counts_df, aes(x = "", y = value, fill = room_types_percentages))+
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity")+
  coord_polar("y", start = 0)+
  scale_fill_brewer("Room Types", palette = "Dark2")+
  ggtitle("Listing Percentage by Room Type")+
  theme(axis.ticks = element_blank(), panel.grid = element_blank(), axis.text = element_blank())+
  geom_text(aes(label = percentages), size = 5, position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5))
pie

Listings By Neighbourhood

The listings seems to be pretty saturated with respect to neighbourhood,it seems that a few neighbourhoods like Westown,Lakeview have higher desity of listings while the others have very low or neiglible listing counts.

It would be interesting to see how this affect the price and income, since higher concentration on listings in a particular are could lead to more competition that woud lead to reduced price

ggplot(dflistings,aes(x=neighbourhood_cleansed,y = (..count..)/sum(..count..)))  +

Analysis by Host Related Data

Number of Hosts Over the years

It looks like the popularity of airbnb with hosts in Chicago kept increasing and reached a peak in year 2015,with some decrease in 2016 ,since we do not have complete data for year 2017 there is a huge drop for year 2017

tempdf <- dflistings %>% group_by(as.numeric(format(dflistings$host_since,"%Y")))

tempHostCount<- dflistings %>% group_by(Year= as.numeric(format(dflistings$host_since,"%Y"))) %>% summarise(NumberOfHosts = length(unique(host_id)))


ggplot(tempHostCount, aes( as.factor(tempHostCount$Year),NumberOfHosts)) + geom_bar(stat= 'identity') +

  ylab("Count Of Hosts")+
  xlab("Years")

There is not really a noticeable trend for what month of the year the hosts join,although the number in consistently good for June and July !!!

## Anaysis by Time Factor

We tried to plot a graph of overal availability throught the time period available in the date set to check the busy time period for the available listings

It looks like until July the listings were pretty booked and availablity increased after the July 2017. The prices keeps on fluctuating day to day.

tempdf <- dfCalendars%>% group_by(date)%>%

This chart might not be give a good idea about trend from 2017 to 2018 due incomplete data !!!! So, analysisng data over the months might help to get some insights

tempdf <- dfCalendars%>% group_by(year)%>% filter(available == 't') %>% summarize(BookedDays = n(),Price = mean(price))

ggplot(tempdf, aes(year, Price)) + geom_bar(stat="identity")

Clearly, Chicago seems to be highly booked in the month of May , possiblity due to good weather ,The number of booked days are also high during December,this could be possibly due to winter vacations !!

With respect to price,the prices peak in the month of June and July,while they are low through the months December to Feb, Again weather and vacation are two possible explantions for these changes

tempdf <- dfCalendars%>% group_by(month)%>% filter(available == 'f') %>% summarize(BookedDays = n() )

5.ActiveDays vs Price

Calculated Field with first and Last Review i.e duration the Listing was active

The graph shows a leaflike structure,for listings with less number of active days,he price range is narrow and it widens with increased number of active days

dflistings$ActiveDays <- difftime(dflistings$last_review,dflistings$first_review, units = "days") # days
dflistings$ActiveDays[is.na(dflistings$ActiveDays)] <- 0

ggplot(dflistings, aes(log(price), log(as.integer(ActiveDays))  ,color = property_type)) +  geom_point() +
      facet_wrap(~ dflistings$room_type)
